It is seductive, slightly mournful, as though every song was being sung on the last passionate evening of two lovers' lives and the imminent sorrow of parting was already lifting them up, away, apart forever.

Mr. Rahman, you have been my favorite Indian composer since I began watching films in 2008 after the first anniversary of my daughter death from a long-time illness. Your music helped me so much in those first year as purchased many films. I eventually learned to recognize your music without checking the credits because of your distinctive style.  I have seen the first two films of Vasundhara Das and have enjoyed her acting as well as her singing.  She is a gifted artist in both crafts and her voice is also very recognizable for the lyrical quality and emotional context she presents. 

You have provided the loveliest musical tapestries in which several of my favorite films have been incorporated. I have the soundtracks to Dil Se, Taal, Swades, Lagaan, Jodhaa Akbar, and Slumdog Millionaire. Each one contains such deep emotional resonance with the film that moves me to laughter, cheers, tears, contemplation, hope, and joy whenever I watch them. Lagaan and Swades especially have often inspired me when I have had very difficult challenges. All the stories are powerful, yet your music gives them life. It encouraged me deeply during the first years of mourning for my daughter. Something very spiritual happens with the chords and notes as they reach our painful feelings and turns us towards hope. Contemporary western music seldom meets one's needs when we experience this sorrow because our culture has a fierce resistance to expressing it after loved ones die. Many Hindi films helped me grieve in full measure so that I could eventually heal.

It ihas been a rich blessing to hear your gorgeous, sensitive music. Thank you so much for what you have shared with the world and with this older listener in the Pacific Northwest State of Washington in the US.
